French scientists have solved the 
mystery of how one of the world’s smallest frogs can croak and hear 
other amphibians without possessing an eardrum.

Gardiner’s
frogs from the Seychelles islands, which are just one centimetre long, 
were thought to be deaf, but the research revealed they actually hear 
sounds through their mouths.

Using X-rays, the scientists discovered the frogs’ mouths act as a resonator 
or amplifier for the frequencies ‘spoken’ by the species.

